docs.lead_paragraph: The first water birth unit on Long Island, built a year ago by the Nassau University Medical Center, has finally produced its first infant, a baby girl born on March 30 to a couple from Bay Shore. The financially strapped hospital invested $10,000 in the reconstructed labor room, said Richard B. Turan, the president of the medical center, ''because of a need to keep up with the times and to serve the people of this region much better.'' No additional personnel were required for the unit, he added, because of its close proximity to the labor and delivery suite, where more than 2,000 babies are born each year.

headline.main: Nassau Medical Greets Its First Water Birth

docs.lead_paragraph: FROM the docks in Elizabeth and Camden, from cargo flights out of Newark International Airport and on rails extending to Canada and Mexico, New Jersey is extending its reach far into the global economy. Blueberry wine to Tokyo and cranberry juice to the Caribbean. Typhoid tests to Bangladesh. Valves for rocket launchers and fiber-optic switches for Europe. For that matter, the world's entire supply of Calvin Klein cologne is exported from Mount Olive.

headline.main: New Jersey Makes, the World Takes

docs.abstract: Article on New Jersey's far-reaching and expanding role in global economy; state, with proximity to well-developed ports and air cargo facilities, ranked eighth in US in exports, at $25.93 billion in 2001; international trade has protected state somewhat from worldwide economic slowdown; New Jersey is host to foreign companies that base their US headquarters or manufacturing operations there; photos (L)

docs.lead_paragraph: The provincial government of Quebec granted 14 Inuit, or Eskimo, villages a $450 million development program today in exchange for their agreement to expand hydroelectric generating capacity in the northern reaches of the province. Inuit leaders who signed the agreement, which was negotiated in secret talks over the last month and drawn up in the form of a treaty, described it as a new and important recognition of their rights as a self-governing people.
